  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Attempting to Use Non-Qualifying Investments</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">The 2022 Active Investor Plus overhaul specifically excludes government bonds, bank deposits, and passive investments. Many applicants familiar with older investor visa programs don't realize the rules changed. Only "active" investments in growth assets qualify—verify your investment plan with Immigration NZ or a licensed adviser before applying.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Underestimating the "Active" Contribution Requirement</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Active Investor Plus isn't just about money—you're expected to contribute business expertise to New Zealand. This might include mentoring NZ companies, joining advisory boards, or sharing industry knowledge. Applications that treat it as purely passive investment may face scrutiny or rejection.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Skipping Health Insurance Because It's Not Mandatory</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">While health insurance isn't a visa requirement, New Zealand's public healthcare is not available to investor visa holders (except ACC for injuries). A serious illness without insurance could cost NZD 100,000+. The savings from skipping insurance aren't worth the catastrophic risk.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Failing to Transfer Funds Within 12 Months</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">After visa approval, you must transfer your investment funds to qualifying NZ investments within 12 months. Missing this deadline can jeopardize your visa status. Plan your fund transfer and investment deployment before approval—don't scramble after receiving the visa.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Not Using a Licensed Immigration Adviser</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">New Zealand requires immigration advisers to be licensed. Using an unlicensed adviser can result in poor advice and wasted application fees. For high-value investor visas, professional guidance is essential—verify your adviser is registered with the Immigration Advisers Authority (IAA).</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in New Zealand -->
  <section id="healthcare" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Healthcare in New Zealand</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      New Zealand has a unique healthcare system that combines public hospitals with strong private sector options. As an investor visa holder, you'll rely on private healthcare for illness while ACC covers any accident-related injuries.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">The ACC System: Injury Coverage for Everyone</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      New Zealand's ACC (Accident Compensation Corporation) is a no-fault insurance scheme covering everyone in the country—visitors, workers, and residents alike. If you're injured in New Zealand, ACC covers:
    </p>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-green-200 bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-green-900 mb-3">ACC Benefits</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-green-800">
          <li>Medical treatment for injuries</li>
          <li>Surgery and hospital stays (injury-related)</li>
          <li>Rehabilitation and physiotherapy</li>
          <li>Weekly compensation if unable to work</li>
          <li>Covers sports and adventure activities</li>
          <li>Motor vehicle accident coverage</li>
          <li>Work-related injury protection</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="border border-blue-200 bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-blue-900 mb-3">ACC Trade-off</h4>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-blue-800">
          <li>• Cannot sue for personal injury (ACC replaces lawsuits)</li>
          <li>• Coverage only for accidental injury, not illness</li>
          <li>• Some gaps in coverage (eg. stress-related conditions)</li>
          <li>• Funded by levies on employers and vehicle registration</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Private Healthcare Quality</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      New Zealand's private healthcare is excellent, particularly in major cities. As an investor visa holder paying privately, you'll have access to:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Modern hospitals:</strong> Well-equipped facilities in Auckland, Wellington, Christchurch</li>
      <li><strong>Short waiting times:</strong> Private patients typically seen within days</li>
      <li><strong>English-speaking care:</strong> No language barriers for treatment</li>
      <li><strong>Specialist access:</strong> Direct referral to specialists without GP gatekeeping</li>
      <li><strong>International standard:</strong> Many NZ doctors trained in UK, US, or Australia</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Major Private Hospital Networks</h3>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 mb-6">
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Southern Cross Hospitals</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Largest private hospital group. Present in Auckland, Wellington, Christchurch, Hamilton, and other cities.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Mercy Hospital</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Catholic-affiliated hospitals in Auckland and Dunedin. Excellent surgical and specialist services.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Wakefield Hospital</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-neutral-600">Wellington's main private hospital. Comprehensive surgical and medical services.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-3">Path to Public Healthcare</h3>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Once you obtain residence (after the 4-year investment period), you become eligible for New Zealand's public healthcare system:
    </p>

    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2 mb-6">
      <li><strong>Subsidized GP visits:</strong> NZD 20-50 per visit (vs. NZD 80-120 privately)</li>
      <li><strong>Free hospital care:</strong> Public hospitals provide free treatment for residents</li>
      <li><strong>Subsidized prescriptions:</strong> Maximum NZD 5 per prescription item</li>
      <li><strong>Waiting lists apply:</strong> Non-urgent surgery may have waits</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-lg p-4">
      <p class="text-blue-800">
        <strong>Hybrid approach:</strong> Many long-term NZ residents maintain private insurance even after gaining residence rights. This provides faster access to specialists and elective surgery while using the public system for emergencies and routine care. Budget NZD 200-400/month for ongoing private coverage post-residence.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happened to the old Investor 1 and Investor 2 categories?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          They were replaced in 2022 by the Active Investor Plus visa. The old categories allowed passive investments like government bonds; the new program requires "active" investments in growth assets that benefit New Zealand's economy. If you applied under the old system before the change, your application would have been processed under those rules.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to live in New Zealand during the 4-year investment period?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          There is no minimum stay requirement for the Active Investor Plus visa during the investment period. However, you must maintain your qualifying investment in New Zealand for the full 4 years. For residence application after the investment period, you'll need to demonstrate commitment to New Zealand, which typically includes spending meaningful time in the country.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I include my family in the investor visa application?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Your partner and dependent children can be included in your application. Each family member must meet health and character requirements, and each should have their own health insurance. Family members receive the same visa conditions and can work, study, and live in New Zealand.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does ACC work if I get injured skiing or doing adventure sports?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          ACC covers everyone in New Zealand for accidental injuries, regardless of visa status. If you're injured skiing, bungy jumping, or hiking, ACC covers your treatment costs. This is automatic—no registration required. However, ACC only covers injuries, not illness. Your private health insurance covers illness and non-injury conditions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the path from investor visa to citizenship?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          After completing the 4-year investment period, you can apply for residence. As a resident, you can then apply for citizenship after 5 years of residence (meeting presence requirements—typically 1,350 days physically present). Total timeline: approximately 9+ years from investor visa to citizenship eligibility.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is the Entrepreneur Visa easier than Active Investor Plus?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          The Entrepreneur Work Visa has a much lower capital requirement (NZD 100,000 vs. NZD 5+ million), but requires active business operation and is points-based. You must run your business full-time and demonstrate benefit to New Zealand. It's a different pathway—better for hands-on entrepreneurs, not passive investors. Success rate is lower than investor visas due to stringent business viability requirements.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      New Zealand's Active Investor Plus visa offers access to one of the world's most desirable countries for high-net-worth individuals willing to make substantial, active investments. The 2022 program redesign ensures that investor capital contributes meaningfully to New Zealand's economy—not just parked in passive instruments.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-4">
      The NZD 5-15 million threshold is significant, but New Zealand delivers exceptional value: political stability, clean environment, world-class education, English-speaking society, and a lifestyle that emphasizes work-life balance. The no-minimum-stay requirement during the investment period provides flexibility for those maintaining international commitments.
    </p>

    <p class="mb-6">
      For those with less capital, the Entrepreneur Visa at NZD 100,000 offers a hands-on alternative—but requires full-time business operation. Health insurance is essential regardless of pathway; while ACC covers accidents, you'll rely on private insurance for any illness until you obtain residence after 4+ years.
    </p>

    <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6">
      <h3 class="font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-3">Bottom Line</h3>
      <p class="text-primary-800 mb-4">
        New Zealand's Active Investor Plus is ideal for high-net-worth individuals seeking exceptional quality of life in an English-speaking, stable democracy. The investment must be "active"—growth companies, managed funds, or equities—not passive bonds. Budget NZD 4,000-8,000 annually for health insurance (not mandatory but essential). Work with licensed immigration advisers and understand the 4-year investment commitment before applying.
      </p>
